04280nam a22006615i 9780801466311DE-B159720230103011142.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230103t20132013nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808014663117 a10.7591/97808014663112doi  a(DE-B1597)478513  a(OCoLC)979622636  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aLIT0060002bisacsh1 aOng, Walter J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aInterfaces of the Word :bStudies in the Evolution of Consciousness and Culture /cWalter J. Ong. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (352 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tI. CLEAVAGE AND GROWTH -- t1. Transformations of the Word and Alienation -- tII. THE SEQUESTRATION OF VOICE -- t2. The Writer's Audience Is Always a Fiction -- t3. Media Transformation: The Talked Book -- t4. African Talking Drums and Oral Noetics -- t5. "I See What You Say": Sense Analogues for Intellect -- tIII. CLOSURE AND PRINT -- t6. Typographic Rhapsody: Ravisius Textor, Zwinger, and Shakespeare -- t7. From Epithet to Logic: Miltonic Epic and the Closure of Existence -- t8. The Poem as a Closed Field: The Once New Criticism and the Nature of Literature -- t9. Maranatha: Death and Life in the Text of the Book -- t10. From Mimesis to Irony: Writing and Print as Integuments of Voice -- tIV. PRESENT AND FUTURE -- t11. Voice and the Opening of Closed Systems -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDrawing on a wide range of disciplines—linguistics, phenomenological analysis, cultural anthropology, media studies, and intellectual history—Walter J. Ong offers a reasoned and sophisticated view of human consciousness different in many respects from that of structuralism. The essays in Interfaces of the Word are grouped around the dialectically related themes of change or alienation and growth or integration. Among the subjects Ong covers are the origins of speech in mother tongues; the rise and final erosion of nonvernacular learned languages; and the fictionalizing of audiences that is enforced by writing. Other essays treat the idiom of African talking drums, the ways new media interface with the old, and the various connections between specific literary forms and shifts in media that register in the work of Shakespeare and Milton and in movements such as the New Criticism. Ong also discusses the paradoxically nonliterary character of the Bible and the concerted blurring of fiction and actuality that marked much drama and narrative toward the close of the twentieth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 03. Jan 2023) 4aCultural Studies. 4aHistory Of Science. 4aHistory. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z97831105361570 cprintz978080149240240uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080146631140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801466311423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801466311/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK